{{good article}}
{{italic title}}
[[File:Láminas 8 y 9 del Códice de Dresden.jpg|thumb|upright 1.3|''Dresden Codex'', pages 10 and 11]]
The '''''Dresden Codex''''' is a [[Maya civilization|Mayan]] book, the oldest surviving from the Americas, dating to the 13th or 14th century. The [[codex]] was rediscovered in the city of [[Dresden, Germany]], hence the book's present name. It is located in the museum of the [[Saxon State and University Library Dresden|Saxon State Library]].

The book suffered serious water damage during World War II. The pages are made of [[Amate]], {{convert|8|in|cm}} high, and can be folded [[Accordion|accordion-style]]; when unfolded the codex is {{convert|12|ft|m}} long. It is [[Mesoamerican writing systems|written]] in [[Mayan hieroglyph]]s and refers to an original text of some three or four hundred years earlier, describing local history and [[Maya astronomy|astronomical tables]].

== Description ==
The ''Dresden Codex'' contains 78 pages with decorative board covers on the front and back.{{sfn|Lyons|2011|p=85}} Most pages have writing on both sides.{{sfn|Lyons|2011|p=85}} They have a border of red paint,{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=19}} although many have lost this framing due to age deterioration. The pages are generally divided into three sections; students of the codex have arbitrary labeled these sections '' a '',  ''b'' , and '' c ''.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=19}} Some pages have just two horizontal sections, while one has four and another five sections.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=19}} The individual sections with their own theme are generally separated by a red vertical line. Sections are generally divided into two to four columns.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=19}}

The ''Dresden Codex'' is one of four hieroglyphic [[Maya codices]] that survived the [[Spanish Inquisition]] in the [[New World]].{{sfn|Ruggles|2005|p=133}} Three, the Dresden, [[Madrid Codex (Maya)|Madrid]], and [[Paris Codex|Paris codices]], are named after the city where they were ultimately rediscovered.{{sfn|Ruggles|2005|p=133}}{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=3}} The fourth is the ''[[Grolier Codex]]'', located at the [[Grolier Club]] in New York City.{{sfn|Sharer|2006|p=129}} The ''Dresden Codex'' is held by the Saxon State and University Library Dresden (SLUB Dresden, Saxon State Library) in Dresden, Germany.{{sfn|Coe|1982|p=4}}{{sfn|Sharer|2006|p=127}} The Maya codices all have about the same size pages, with a height of about {{convert|20|cm}} and a width of {{convert|10|cm}}.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=3}}

The pictures and [[glyphs]] were painted by skilled craftsmen using thin brushes and vegetable dyes.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=3, 15, 16}} Black and red were the main colors used for many of the pages.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=3, 15, 16, 122}} Some pages have detailed backgrounds in shades of yellow, green, and the [[Maya blue|Mayan blue]].{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=15, 122}} The codex was written by eight different scribes, who all had their own writing style, glyph designs, and subject matter.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=3, 15}}

== History ==
[[File:Dresden Codex pp.58-62 78.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Six pages (55–59, 74) on eclipses (left), multiplication tables, and a flood (far right)]]
The ''Dresden Codex'' is described by historian [[J. Eric S. Thompson]] as writings of the indigenous people of the [[Yucatán Peninsula]] in southeastern [[Mexico]]. Maya historians Peter J. Schmidt, Mercedes de la Garza, and Enrique Nalda confirm this.{{sfn|Nalda|1998|p=210}} Thompson further narrows the probable origin of the ''Dresden Codex'' to the area of [[Chichen Itza]], because certain picture symbols in the codex are only found on monuments in that location. He also argues that the astronomical tables would support this as the place of origin. Thompson claims that the people of the Yucatán Peninsula were known to have done such studies around 1200 A.D. Thompson also notes the similar ceramic designs in the Chichen Itza area which are known to have ceased in the early thirteenth century.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=16}} British historian [[Clive Ruggles]] suggests, based on the analyses of several scholars, that the ''Dresden Codex'' is a copy and was originally written between the twelfth and fourteenth centuries.{{sfn|Ruggles|2005|p=134}} Thompson narrows the date closer to 1200 to 1250.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=15–16}} Maya archaeologist [[Linton Satterthwaite]] puts the date when it was made as no later than 1345.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=15}} It is the oldest surviving book from the Americas.{{sfn|Lyons|2011|p=85}}{{sfn|Anzovin|2000|p=197}}

[[Johann Christian Götze]] (1692–1749), German theologian and director of the [[Sächsische Landesbibliothek|Royal Library at Dresden]], purchased the codex from a private owner in Vienna in 1739 while traveling to Italy.{{sfn|Sharer|2006|p=127}}{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=16}}{{sfn|Lyons|2011|p=86}} Thompson speculates that the codex was sent as a tribute to [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]] by [[Hernán Cortés]], governor of Mexico, since examples of local writings and other Maya items were sent to the king in 1519 when he was living in Vienna.{{sfn|Sharer|2006|p=127}}{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=17}}

[[File:Humboldt 1810 pp 47 48 50 51 52.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|First publication in 1811 by Humboldt, who repainted five pages for [https://books.google.com/books?id=6x4UDAEACAAJ&dq=Atlas+g%C3%A9ographique+et+physique+du+royaume+de+la+Nouvelle+Espagne+1811&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCwoqeiqnQAhWCZCYKHUpNBpYQ6AEIITAB his atlas]]]
[[Alexander von Humboldt]] published pages 47–52 from the ''Dresden Codex'' in his 1811 atlas ''[[Alexander von Humboldt#Mexico 1803.E2.80.9304|Vues des Cordillères et Monuments des Peuples Indigènes de l'Amérique]]'', the first reproduction of any of its pages. The first copy of the codex was published by [[Edward King, Viscount Kingsborough|Lord Kingsborough]] in his 1831 ''[[Antiquities of Mexico]]''. In 1828 [[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque]] had identified this book as being of Maya origin based on its glyphs looking like those found at [[Palenque]].{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=17}}<ref name=LongAgo>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Architecture Long Ago |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/7784188// |newspaper=New York Times |location=New York City |date=July 12, 1896 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> Historian [[Cyrus Thomas]] made a connection between the codex and the 260 year cycle ("Ahau Katun") of the Maya calendar and the 365 days in a year.<ref name=LongAgo/>{{sfn|Keane|2011|p=392}}{{sfn|Thomas|1894|p=15}}{{sfn|American Anthropologist|1891|p=299}}{{sfn|Smithsonian Institution|1897|p=36}} Ruggles shows that in the codex the Maya related their 260-day calendar to celestial bodies, especially [[Venus]] and [[Mars]].{{sfn|Ruggles|2005|p=257}}

The codex has played a key role in the deciphering of [[Mayan script|Mayan hieroglyphs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slub-dresden.de/en/collections/manuscripts/the-dresden-maya-codex/ |title=SLUB Dresden: The Dresden Maya-Codex |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104161002/http://www.slub-dresden.de/en/collections/manuscripts/the-dresden-maya-codex/ |archivedate=4 January 2017 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref> Dresden librarian [[Ernst Förstemann|Ernst Wilhelm Förstemann]] published the first complete [[facsimile]] in 1880.{{sfn|Coe|1982|p=3}} He deciphered the calendar section of the codex, including the [[Maya numerals]] used therein.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=71,81,85,105}} Förstemann determined that these numbers, along with deities and day names, related to the [[Mayan calendar]] and the [[Mayan Long Count calendar]].{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=21,25,62}} In the 1950s [[Yuri Knorozov]] used a phonetic approach based on the [[De Landa alphabet]] for decoding the codex, which was followed up in the 1980s by other scholars that did additional deciphering based on this concept.<ref name=Gugliotta>{{cite news |last= Gugliotta |first=Guy |date=May 21, 2013 |title=New tool for digging into mysteries of Maya culture. |url= |newspaper=Washington Post (pg E5)  |location= Washington, D.C. |access-date= |quote=''And Soviet linguistics expert Yuri Knorozov discovered that de Landa's alphabet was actually a phonetic syllabary.'' }}</ref>

Paul Schellhas in 1897 and 1904 assigned letters to gods for specific glyphs since they had several possible names. For example God D could be Hunab Ku Itzam Na among several other names and God A could be Cizin (god of death) among others.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=31}} The Schellhas system of assigning letters for the gods represented by certain glyphs as a noncommittal system was adopted by later researchers of Maya codices.{{sfn|Taube|1992|p=6}}

The ''Dresden Codex'' contains accurate astronomical tables,{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=63–69}} which are recognized by students of the codex for its detailed [[Maya astronomy#Venus|Venus tables]] and [[Maya calendar#Lunar Series|lunar tables]].{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=62–71}} The lunar series has intervals correlating with eclipses, while the Venus tables correlate with the movements of the planet Venus.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=63–69}} The codex also contains astrological tables and ritual schedules.{{sfn|Ruggles|2005|p=134}}{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=32–47}} The religious references show in a cycle of a 260-day ritual calendar the important Maya royal events.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=3,63,73}} The codex also includes information on the Maya new-year ceremony tradition.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=89–93}} The rain god [[Chaac]] is represented 134 times.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=27}}

== Image ==
{{Wide image|DresdenCodexCorrectReadingSequence.jpg|9500 px|The complete ''Dresden Codex'' in the correct reading sequence (pages 1–24, 46–74, 25–45) from left to right, including empty pages}}

== Deterioration and pagination ==
[[File:DresdenCodexSheetsAglio.png|thumb|upright=1.3|First page sequencing of the codex by Agostino Aglio]]
[[File:DresdenCodexOriginalSheets2.png|thumb|upright=1.3|Correct reading order of the pages within the codex]]
[[File:DresdenCodexSheetsToday.png|thumb|upright=1.3|The presentation of the ''Dresden Codex'' since 1945]]

Italian artist and engraver [[Agostino Aglio]], starting in 1826, became the first to transcribe and illustrate the codex completely for Lord Kingsborough, who published it in his nine volumes of ''[[Antiquities of Mexico]]'' in 1831&ndash;1848. The codex then had some damage due to handling, sunlight, and moisture. It received direct water damage that was significantly destructive from being kept in a flooded basement during the [[bombing of Dresden in World War II]].{{sfn|Coe|1982|p=3}} German historian G. Zimmerman noted that the damage was extreme on pages 2, 4, 24, 28, 34, 38, 71 and 72.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|p=19}} Certain details of the glyph images have been lost because of this. This shows when the current codex is compared to the Kingsborough copies of 1831-1848 and the Förstemann facsimile editions of 1880 and 1892.{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=18-19}}{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=297}}

Today’s page numbers were assigned to the codex by [[Agostino Aglio]] when he became the first to transcribe the manuscript in 1825/26. For this, he divided the original codex into two parts, labeled ''Codex A'' and ''Codex B''.  He sequenced ''Codex A'' on the front side followed by its back side, with the same order on ''Codex B''. Today, historians such as Helmut Deckert and Ferdinand Anders understand that a codex reading should traverse the complete front side followed by the complete back side of the manuscript, i.e., pages 1–24 followed by 46-74 and 25-45.{{sfn|Deckert|1989|pp=30-43}} The librarian K. C. Falkenstein adjusted the relative position of pages for “esthetical reasons” in 1836, resulting in today’s two similar length parts.{{sfn|Deckert|1989|p=7}} While deciphering the codex, the  librarian [[Ernst Förstemann|E. W. Förstemann]] noticed an error in Aglio’s page assignment of the sheets 1/45 and 2/44, so he correctly reassigned Aglio’s pages 44 and 45 to become pages 1 and 2.{{sfn|Deckert|1989|pp=32-33}} The reversal of the sheets 6/40, 7/39 and 8/38 is due to an error when the sheets were returned to their protective glass cabinet after drying from the water damage due to the bombing of Dresden in 1945.{{sfn|Deckert|1989|p=41}}

