'''Lanner Group Ltd''' is a software company specialising in [[simulation software]] such as [[discrete event simulation]] and [[predictive simulation]], headquartered in [[Henley-in-Arden]], Warwickshire. The business develops, markets and supports business process simulation and optimisation systems.<ref name="two">[http://www.lanner.com/en/about-us.cfm Lanner Group Company History Page]</ref><ref name="three">{{cite web | url=http://www.wmictcluster.org/events/2009-case-studies/lanner-group | title=West Midlands ICT Case studies 2009 | accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> The company has subsidiaries in the USA, China, France and Germany and a distributor network selling the company's products in 20 different countries.<ref name="four">{{cite web | url=http://www.3i.com/portfolio/companies/lanner-group.html/ | title=3i Investment portfolio | accessdate=9 September 2010}}</ref> Lanner Group was formed following a [[Management Buyout]] of ''AT&T Istel'', a spin-off from the operational research department of [[British Leyland]] where, in 1978, the world's first ''visual interactive simulation tool'' was developed.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hollocks |first=BW|title=Forty years of discrete-event simulation-a personal reflection|journal=Journal of the Operational Research Society |volume=7|year=2006|pages=1383–1399 |doi=10.1057/palgrave.jors.2602128}}</ref> Lanner Group services automotive, aviation, criminal justice, defence and aerospace, financial services and contact centres, food and beverage, health, logistics and supply chain, manufacturing, nuclear, oil and gas, pharmaceutical, and consumer health industries.<ref name="six">{{cite web |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=731838 |title=Lanner Group Limited |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek, Bloomberg.com|trans-title=company overview |accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref>

== Company history ==
Lanner Group formed in 1996 after completing a Management Buyout from ''AT&T Istel'';<ref name="two" /> the company was initially named ''SEE WHY SOLUTIONS'' and was incorporated in 1995.<ref name="six" /> Lanner Group's previous owner, AT&T Istel, formerly known as [[ISTEL]], was initially called ''BL Systems'', and was a [[Corporate spin-off|spin out]] formed in 1979 following a [[Merger]] of all the computer departments under the then [[British Leyland]] umbrella. BL System's ''SEE WHY'' tool, programmed in [[Fortran 77]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.facsim.org/node/121 | title=Programming Language Benchmarks | date=29 January 2008 | author=Allen MJ| accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> and launched in 1980,<ref name="two" /> was the world's first commercially available visual interactive simulation package and the precursor to Lanner Group's current core software product ''WITNESS''.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Gilman AR, Billingham C |title=A tutorial on SEE WHY and WITNESS|journal=Proceedings of the 21st conference on Winter simulation|year=1989|pages=192–200|location=New York, NY|publisher=Association for Computing Machinery|url=http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/76738.76761|doi=10.1145/76738.76761|format=pdf|accessdate=16 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Diamond R, Harrell CR, Henriksen JO, Nordgren WB, Pegden CD, Rohrer MW, Waller AP, Law AM |title=Current and future status of simulation software (panel)|journal=Proceedings of the 34th conference on Winter simulation: exploring new frontiers|year=2002|pages=1633–1640|publisher=Winter Simulation Conference}}</ref> WITNESS was the first of the industrial strength ''4GL'' simulators.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dynamic.co.kr/Witness_Training_Center/Articles/Bpmn%20-%20simulation.pdf |vauthors=Enstone LR, Clark MF | title=BPMN and simulation |date=April 2006 | format=pdf | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The WITNESS system was launched on [[IBM PC]] in 1986<ref name="two" /> and has been revised frequently since.<ref name="two" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/66333/1/Thesis_Lanting_Lu.pdf | author=Lanting Lu | title=Modelling breakdown durations in simulation models of engine assembly lines, PhD thesis |date=May 2009 | format=pdf | location=School of Mathematics, University of Southampton | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worksmanagement.co.uk/article/27287/Lanners-Witness-simulation-software-gets-new-licence-manager.aspx | author=Staff Reporter | title=Lanner's Witness simulation software gets new licence manager | date=26 August 2010 | publisher=Works Management News | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The latest version of Lanner's Witness was released in summer 2017.<ref>https://www.lanner.com/technology/witness-simulation-software.html</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.brothersoft.com/latest-edition-of-witness-software-released-allows-any-business-to-optimize-process-performance-with-simulation-software-fast/201011-41132.html | author=Brothersoft News| date= 12 November 2010 | title=Latest Edition of WITNESS Software Released: Allows Any Business to Optimize Process Performance with Simulation Software – Fast | publisher=brothersoft.com | accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref>

The applications of the FORTRAN 77 / WITNESS interface have been subject to further academic [[Research and Development]].<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=((Rotab Khana MR)), Harlock SC, Leaf GA |title=Computer simulation of production systems for woven fabric manufacture|journal=Computers & Industrial Engineering|volume=37|issue=4|date=1 December 1999|pages=745–756|doi=10.1016/s0360-8352(00)00009-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Goyal SK, Mehta K, Kodali R, Deshmukh SG |title=Simulation for analysis of scheduling rules for a flexible manufacturing system|journal=Integrated Manufacturing Systems|volume=6|issue=5|year=1995|pages=21–26|doi=10.1108/09576069510093442}}</ref> Since 1985 the company has supported its simulation software academic program. Over 100 universities worldwide have been involved since the program began.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mhwmagazine.co.uk/news-item.asp?id=6981 | date=5 July 2010 | title=Simulation modeling software company Lanner Group partner Ingram school of engineering | publisher=Materials Handling World Magazine | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref>

Lanner Group continued to develop the WITNESS platform further in parallel to developing its mainstay product of the same name, and since 2002 has introduced new systems providing niche simulation packages for police and healthcare organisations called ''PRISM'' and ''PX-Sim'' respectively.<ref name="two" /><ref name="three" /> In 2006 the company unveiled a [[Java (programming language)|Java]] based simulation engine called ''L-SIM'' which is embedded in [[Business Process Management]] (BPM) solutions software.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Waller AP, Clark MF, Enstone LR |title=L-SIM : Simulating BPMN Diagrams with a Purpose Built Engine | journal=Proceedings of the 2006 Winter Simulation Conference (WSC 06)|year=2006 | pages=591–597 | publisher=Winter Simulation Conference | isbn=1-4244-0500-9}}</ref> In May the same year, a technology partnership with BPM solution provider [[IDS Scheer]] was announced.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ids-scheer.com/en/News/IDS_Scheer_and_Lanner_announce_partnership_for_Java_based_business_process_simulation/1680.html?referer=23380 | title=IDS Scheer and Lanner announce partnership for Java based business process simulation | publisher=IDS-Sheer.com | accessdate=21 November 2010}}</ref> The L-SIM product is now the simulation engine of IDS Scheer's ARIS Business Simulator.<ref>{{cite web | author=Bob Violino | url=http://www.ciozone.com/index.php/Management/BPM-3-Vendors-To-Watch.html | title=BPM: 3 Vendors To Watch | publisher=CIO Zone | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> The company's WITNESS platform technology is therefore embedded into current [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[SAP AG|SAP]], and [[IBM]] [[Business Analysis|BPA]] products.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lanner.com/en/business-partners.cfm | title=Lanner Group company website 'Business Partners' page | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref>

From 1996 to 2010 the company's main investor was private equity company [[3i]]. On 18 March 2010 Lanner Group announced that it had secured a £3 million new investment deal with ''NVM Private Equity'' replacing [[3i]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worksmanagement.co.uk/article/23429/Lanner-Group-secures-new-funding-with-NVM-tol-execute-growth-plans.aspx | title=Lanner Group secures new funding with NVM to execute growth plans | author=Brian Tinham | publisher=Works Management news | date=22 March 2010 | accessdate=23 October 2010}}</ref> 3i continues to retain an interest in Lanner Group as a small minority investor.<ref name="four" />

